{
  "id": "colinhacks_zod_5130",
  "repo_name": "colinhacks/zod",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/colinhacks/zod",
  "base_commit": "c6a0ca3d8baea3998307de7b56226ab41d2c3fd5",
  "pr_number": 5130,
  "issue_number": 5127,
  "issue_title": "Stricter UUID validation should allow sentinel value of max UUID as valid.",
  "issue_body": "\nWith zod v4 validation of uuid was [updated](\nhttps://zod.dev/v4/changelog?id=stricter-uuid) and now corresponds stricter RFC spec. But RFC 9562 spec defines 2 special UUIDs - Nil and [Max (RFC)](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9562#name-max-uuid) which are `00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000` and `ffffffff-ffff-ffff-ffff-ffffffffffff` correspondingly.\n\nZod validation of `z.uuid()` supports Nil UUID fine but treats [Max UUID as invalid](https://zod-playground.vercel.app?appdata=N4IgzgxgFgpgtgQxALhALwHQFcsEsAmAFAJQgA0IAbggDZYxgoDaIA5AGadecC03fXAb24iurEAF0KlGACcwuAPYA7FCAAsGAAwYAjAHZyIXGABai-AFlcy3Cna0wMAL5A). \n\nThis does not look correct.\n\nSpec outlines it as max uuid can be used as a special value:\n\n> A Max UUID value can be used as a sentinel value in situations where a 128-bit UUID is required, but a concept such as \"end of UUID list\" needs to be expressed and is reserved for such use as needed for implementation-specific situations. Note that the Max UUID value falls within the range of the \"yet-to-be defined\" future UUID variant as per the last row of [Table 1](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9562#table1) rather than the variant defined by this document.\n\nAnd although max uuid falls into \"Reserved for future definition\" category of a spec (because of `F` in variant field) - it also serves as a valid sentinel value in current spec and should be allowed.\n\nFor anyone who needs a quick fix - switching from z.uuid() to z.guid() as doc suggesting, allows max uuid value, [as expected](https://zod-playground.vercel.app?appdata=N4IgzgxgFgpgtgQxALhALwHQHMCuBLAEwAoBKEAGhADcEAbHGMFAbRAHIAzL7rgWh-7dBfHqO5sQAXUpUYAJzB4A9gDsUIACwYADBgCMAdgog8YAFpKCAWTwq8KDnTAwAvkA).\n\nThis issue may have a broader impact as there are multiple packages that generate code from openapi definitions and use zod for schema validation - so `z.uuid()` is not so easily replaced with `z.guid()` in code-generated models.\n",
  "merged_at": "2025-08-23T06:45:27Z",
